e, England, United Kingdom","Lund-in-the-Woods, Yorkshire, England":"Lund, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Constable","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southeastern): occupational name for the law-enforcement officer of a parish, from Middle English, Old French <i>conestable</i>, <i>cunestable</i>, from Late Latin <i>comes stabuli</i> ‘officer of the stable’. The title was also borne by various other officials during the Middle Ages, including the chief officer of a household or court, or a military officer, and this may in some cases be the source of the surname.","Americanized form of Dutch <b>Constapel</b>, an occupational name for the chief gunner aboard a ship or in the garrison of a fort."],"variants":[{"name":"Costabile","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Aldo, Antonio, Ciro, Nino, Agnese, Angelo, Duilio, Enrico, Ercole, Franco, Palma.","Italian (southern):","occupational name from medieval Greek <i>kontostablēs</i> ‘chamberlain’, from medieval Latin <i>comes stabuli</i>, literally ‘count of the stable’ (see   Constable  )."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":20,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor Constable was born in 1435, in Willoughby Manor, Lincolnshire, England. She married Sir Henry Lund in 1450, in Lund, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died on 24 July 1485, in Lund, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1435–24 July 1485":"1435–24. juuli 1485","1405–1480":"1405–1480","1440–1488":"1440–1488","1450–1502":"1450–1502","1435–1485":"1435–1485","24 July 1485":"24. juuli 1485","1502":"1502","1435":"1435","9 Sep 1480":"9. september 1480","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1485":"1485","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","1405":"1405","Lund, Yorkshire, England":"Lund, Yorkshire, England","Lund-in-the-Woods, York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Willoughby Manor, Lincolnshire, England":"Willoughby Manor, Lincolnshire, England","Hasfie